    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "t_start": 80,
      "estimated_duration_s": 24,
      "narration_text": "Illustrative numbers: room temperature T = 300 K gives kT \u2248 0.025 eV. A low-frequency microwave mode at \u03bd = 10 GHz has h\u03bd \u2248 0.00004 eV \u2014 tiny compared to kT, so the mode is well-populated and the classical and Planck curves agree. A high-frequency UV mode at \u03bd = 10\u00b9\u2075 Hz has h\u03bd \u2248 4 eV \u2014 far larger than kT, so the Boltzmann factor kills the population. No packets fit. The classical curve would assign this mode full kT; Planck assigns it nearly zero. That suppression at high frequency removes the catastrophe.",
